el Foucault, Paulo Freire, and Erica R. Edwards. How, he asks, can cultural production positively influence Black and Brown material conditions and mobilize collective action "off the page"? How can art-based counterpublics provide a foundation for Black and Brown community organizing? What emerges from Datcher's innovative analysis is a frank assessment of the links between embodied experiences of racialization, as well as a distinctive vision of twentieth- and twenty-first-century American literature as a repository of emancipatory strategies with real-world applications.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aAgent (Philosophy). 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexHispanic American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexSocial aspects. 0aHegemonyzUnited States. 0aLiberalism in literature. 0aLiberty in literature. 0aPower (Social sciences) in literature. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aLiterature : American Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / African-American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2019z978311149143140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438473413423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438473413/original  a978-3-11-149143-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles